'''Christopher Whyte''' (''Crisdean MhicIlleBhain'') is Scottish poet, novelist, translator and critic.

He was born in [[1952]] in [[Glasgow]] and graduated from [[St. Aloysius' College, Glasgow|St. Aloysius' College]] and then from Cambridge University. For many years he lived in Italy before moving back to Scotland in 1985 to teach Scottish literature at [[Glasgow University]] (1990 until 2005). Since then he has lived in [[Budapest]] as a full-time writer.

Whyte first published some translations of modern poetry into [[Gaelic]], including poems by [[Pier Paolo Pasolini]] (first publication, [[1980]]), [[Konstantinos Kavafis]], [[Yannis Ritsos]], [[Anna Akhmatova]]. Then he published two collections of original poetry in Gaelic, ''Uirsgeul'' (''Myth'', 1991) and ''An Tr√†th Duilich'' (''The Difficult Time'', 2002). In the meantime he started to write prose in English and has published four novels, ''Euphemia MacFarrigle and the Laughing Virgin'' (1995), ''The Warlock of Strathearn'' (1997), ''The Gay Decameron'' (1998) and ''The Cloud Machinery'' (2000).  Whyte has also compiled some anthologies of present-day Gaelic poetry and written critical articles and essays.

